The '''Philadelphia Phillies' 2009 season''' was the 127th season in the [[History of the Philadelphia Phillies|history of the franchise]]. The team, managed by [[Charlie Manuel]], began their sixth season at [[Citizens Bank Park]] and defense of their [[2008 World Series]] championship on April 5.  After collecting a third straight [[National League East|Eastern Division]] championship, the Phillies won their second consecutive National League pennant for the first time in franchise history; they were defeated by the [[New York Yankees]] in the [[2009 World Series]].

The Phillies posted a second consecutive winning April to open the season with an 11&ndash;9 record, but the month was marred by the death of "legendary" broadcaster [[Harry Kalas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/story/11625834|title=Legendary Phillies announcer Kalas dead at 73|date=April 13, 2009|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=31 December 2009}}</ref> After opening the month of May against the rival [[New York Mets]], the Phillies met President [[Barack Obama]] to celebrate their World Series victory the previous season, and had two rookie pitchers win consecutive starts for the first time since 2007. Starting pitcher [[Jamie Moyer]] earned his 250th career win during the month, while first baseman [[Ryan Howard]] and outfielder [[Ra<U+00FA>l Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez]] became the first Phillies teammates to hit 10 home runs in the same month. Echoing their strong run in the middle of the [[2008 Philadelphia Phillies season|2008 season]], the Phillies compiled a 16&ndash;4 record in late May and early June, which was countered by weakness during [[interleague play]] in late June. 

After the team's largest victory of the season (22&ndash;1 over the Cincinnati Reds) in early July, five Phillies<U+2014>Howard, Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez, second baseman [[Chase Utley]], and outfielders [[Shane Victorino]] and [[Jayson Werth]]<U+2014>were selected to the [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star team]]. July was the team's best showing of the season, as they compiled their first 20-win month since the [[2001 Philadelphia Phillies season|2001 season]]. The Phillies traded for starting pitcher [[Cliff Lee]] at the end of the month to bolster their starting rotation, who won his first five starts with the team, and signed free-agent pitcher [[Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez]]. In August, [[Eric Bruntlett]] turned the first game-ending [[unassisted triple play]] in National League history, and the second in team history. The following month, the team clinched its third consecutive division championship on September 30, becoming the first Phillies team to make a third straight playoff appearance since the 1976&ndash;1978 Phillies.

Philadelphia defeated the [[Colorado Rockies]] in the [[2009 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]] (NLDS), 3&ndash;1, and the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the [[2009 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]] (NLCS) for the second consecutive year, 4&ndash;1. Howard was named the [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|most valuable player of the NLCS]]. The Phillies were defeated by the Yankees in the World Series, four games to two.

Statistical leaders{{ref label|Stats|A|A}} in batting for the 2009 team included Victorino ([[batting average]], .292), Howard ([[home run]]s, 45; [[run batted in|runs batted in]], 141), and Utley ([[run (baseball)|runs]] scored, 112). For his season accomplishments, Utley won his fourth consecutive [[Silver Slugger Award]]. Pitching leaders included right-handed starting pitcher [[Joe Blanton]] ([[innings pitched]],&nbsp;{{frac|195|1|3}}), left-handed starter {{nowrap|[[J. A. Happ]]}} ([[Win (baseball)|win<U+2013>loss record]],&nbsp;12<U+2013>4), and relief pitcher [[Brad Lidge]] (saves,&nbsp;31). Victorino and shortstop [[Jimmy Rollins]] also won [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award]]s for their play in the field.
{{TOClimit|2}}

==Offseason==
===Departures===
On November 4, following the World Series, the Phillies released third base coach [[Steve Smith (baseball)|Steve Smith]].<ref name="returning coaches">{{cite web|title=Phillies let third-base coach go|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081104&content_id=3664393&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|last=Mandel|first=Ken|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 5, 2008|date=November 4, 2008}}</ref> Smith had been with the Phillies for two years. The Phillies were expected to have the remaining coaches to return for the 2009 season.<ref name="returning coaches"/> However, bench coach [[Jimy Williams]] opted not to return to the Phillies for the 2009 season, notifying the team on November 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081110&content_id=3673979&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title=Williams not returning to Phillies|date=November 10, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 11, 2008}}</ref> [[Charlie Manuel]] had expected Williams to return for the 2009 season, and was surprised that Williams declined. However, Williams left the Phillies on good terms, and Manuel stated that Williams was welcome to come back to the Phillies if he changed his mind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/blogs/2008/11/nov-11-jimy-williams-leaves.html|title=Jimy Williams Leaves|date=November 10, 2008|last=Lauber|first=Scott|work=DelawareOnline.com|publisher=Wilmington News Journal|accessdate=November 11, 2008}}</ref> Left fielder [[Pat Burrell]] became a free agent at the end of the 2008 season, signing with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]], whom the Phillies had defeated in the [[2008 World Series|World Series]], on January 5.  The Phillies did not tender an offer to Burrell following eight seasons. The Phillies also released outfielder [[So Taguchi]] on November 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081105&content_id=3664630&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title=Phillies part ways with Taguchi|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 5, 2008|date=November 5, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken}}</ref> Taguchi had served as a pinch-hitter for the Phillies in 2008, and also replaced Burrell in left field some games. [[Eric Bruntlett]] replaced Taguchi for the latter half of the 2008 season. Relief pitcher [[Tom Gordon]] also filed for free agency, ultimately signing with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arizona.diamondbacks.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20090206&content_id=3805360&vkey=pr_ari&fext=.jsp&c_id=ari|title=D-backs sign Tom Gordon to one-year contract |work=Diamondbacks.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=April 16, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipusMLqp|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref>

===Arrivals===
[[Image:RaulIbanez.jpg|thumb|right|Ra<U+00FA>l Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez signed a three-year contract with the Phillies in December 2008.|alt=A left-handed man in a white baseball uniform and blue batting helmet with a red brim stands in the batter's box. His uniform jersey reads "Phillies" in red text. On the dirt in from of him, the white pentagon-shaped "home plate" and chalk lines are visible.]]
On November 3, the Phillies named [[Rub<U+00E9>n Amaro, Jr.]] to be the general manager after [[Pat Gillick]] retired at the end of a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081103&content_id=3660782&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title= Amaro Jr. takes over reins for Phillies|accessdate=November 3, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=November 3, 2008}}</ref> Amaro previously had a long history with the Phillies, serving as a [[batboy|bat boy]] in the 1980s, a player in the 1990s, and as assistant general manager for the Phillies from 1998 until his appointment as general manager. Gillick remained with the Phillies as an advisor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081103&content_id=3661056&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title=Gillick to remain with Phils as advisor|work=Phillies.MLB.com|accessdate=November 4, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken|date=November 3, 2008}}</ref> On November 13, [[Sam Perlozzo]] joined the Phillies as third base coach and fielding/infield coach after spending the 2008 season in the same position for the [[Seattle Mariners]].<ref name=Perl>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081113&content_id=3678453&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title=Perlozzo joins Phillies' coaching staff|date=November 13, 2008|author=Mandel, Ken|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 14, 2008}}</ref> Perlozzo previously served as the third base coach for the [[New York Mets]], the [[Cincinnati Reds]], and as third base coach, bench coach, and manager for the [[Baltimore Orioles]].<ref name=Perl/> Another former manager, [[Pete Mackanin]], was named the team's new bench coach on November 21; he had been interim manager for the Reds when [[Jerry Narron]] was fired in Cincinnati in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/rumors/post/Phillies-hire-Mackanin-as-bench-coach?urn=mlb,124287|title=Phillies hire Mackanin as bench coach|last=Zedalis|first=Joe|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref> On November 28, the Phillies signed [[Mike Koplove]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081128&content_id=3695159&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|last=Falkoff|first=Robert|date=November 28, 2008|accessdate=December 1, 2008|publisher=Major League Baseball|title=Phillies add Koplove to bullpen}}</ref> Koplove, a right-handed relief pitcher, was optioned to the AAA [[Lehigh Valley IronPigs]] at the end of spring training. On December 16, [[Ra<U+00FA>l Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez]] agreed to play left field for the Phillies in a 3-year, $31.5 millon deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081216&content_id=3718927&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Ibanez excited to join world champs|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|date=December 16, 2008|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref> [[South Korea]]n pitcher [[Chan Ho Park]] officially signed a one-year contract to join the Phillies on January 6,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/p/parkch01.shtml|title=Chan Ho Park Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 26, 2009}}</ref> after agreeing to a deal in principle in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3717580&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|first=Anthony|last=DiComa|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=October 26, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|title=Park agrees to one-year deal with Phils}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090206&content_id=3805110&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Fab four up for Phils' fifth starter job|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=February 6, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 26, 2009}}</ref> Park was originally signed as an insurance policy for the bullpen, as reliever [[J. C. Romero]] was assigned a fifty-game suspension after violating the [[Major League Baseball drug policy]], but won the fifth starter's job in Spring Training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/story/11573963|title=Phillies release veteran outfielder Jenkins, name Park fifth starter|date=March 31, 2009|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=April 3, 2009}}</ref>

===Retentions===
Left-handed reliever [[Scott Eyre]] re-signed with the Phillies after becoming a vital part of the bullpen during the stretch run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081110&content_id=3673608&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils re-sign lefty reliever Eyre|last=Mandel|first=Ken|date=November 10, 2008|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 11, 2008}}</ref> The Phillies re-signed left-handed starter [[Jamie Moyer]] on December 15 after lengthy negotiations. The 46-year-old Moyer was inked to a two-year contract to return to the world champions and kept a key part of the Phillies' postseason rotation intact.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3718004&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies ink Moyer to two-year pact|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|date=December 15, 2008|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref> The team also avoided salary arbitration with first baseman [[Ryan Howard]]'s three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090208&content_id=3809228&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Howard agrees to $54 million contract|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=February 8, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref>

===Injuries===
[[File:Pedro Feliz 2009.jpg|thumb|right|Chase Utley and Pedro Feliz ''(pictured)'' both had offseason surgeries after the 2008 World Series.|alt=A right-handed man in a red batting practice baseball jersey and white baseball pants with red pinstripes stands in a batter's box by home plate.]]
On November 20, second baseman [[Chase Utley]] had hip surgery and was scheduled to be out for four to six months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081120&content_id=3686087&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Utley to undergo hip surgery next week|last=Mandel|first=Ken|date=November 20, 2008|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 21, 2008}}</ref> However, on December 15, Utley said in a press conference that he could be ready for Opening Night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3718210&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsc&c_id=phi|title=Utley Sets His Sights On Opening Day|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> Just under four months later, Utley made his first pre-season game appearance in an intersquad game March 14,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090314&content_id=3985742&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Utley suits up in Minor League game|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=March 14, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=March 18, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipul7vPv|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and his first appearance in actual game competition the next day against the St. Louis Cardinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090315&content_id=3991228&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Ellison's RBI hit in ninth sinks Cards|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=March 15, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=March 18, 2009}}</ref> Third baseman [[Pedro Feliz]] also had surgery on his back to repair a herniated disc on the same day as Utley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delcotimes.com/articles/2009/02/17/sports/doc499a3ab756ac4939080542.txt|title= Feliz easing his way back from surgery|last=Lawrence|first=Ryan|date=February 17, 2009|work=Delaware County Daily Times|accessdate=April 5, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipulvQPo|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Feliz officially returned to Spring Training action on March 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasybaseball.usatoday.com/content/player.asp?sport=Mlb&id=3125|title=Pedro Feliz|date=March 13, 2009|work=USA Today|accessdate=April 5, 2009}}</ref> During Spring Training, starting pitcher [[Cole Hamels]] left training camp on March 16 and flew to Philadelphia to have his left elbow examined by Dr. Michael Ciccotti. Hamels felt tightness in between innings and after he was done pitching for the day. "This will obviously set me back a couple of days, and I don<U+2019>t think that should be a big deal", said Hamels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/spring2009/news/story?id=3984854|title=Hamels' ailing elbow to be checked|date=March 16, 2009|work=ESPN.com|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=March 17, 2009}}</ref> However, the injury threw his Opening Day start against the Braves into doubt, even though Ciccotti found no structural damage in his arm;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090317&content_id=4004206&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Good news for Hamels; opener still iffy|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=March 17, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=March 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/9344352/Doctor:-Hamels-has-no-damage-in-pitching-elbow?CMP=OTC-K9B140813162&ATT=49|title=Doctor: Hamels has no damage in pitching elbow|date=March 17, 2009|work=FOXSports.com|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 5, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipumX8MP|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Brett Myers]] was announced as Hamels' replacement to start Opening Night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090402&content_id=4110340&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Myers prepared for third straight opener|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=April 3, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 5, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipunDvOz|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref>

==Spring Training ==
On November 13, the Phillies announced their [[Spring Training]] schedule.<ref name=springtrain>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081113&content_id=3679016&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies announce 2009 spring schedule|last=Mandel|first=Ken|date=November 13, 2008|accessdate=November 14, 2008}}</ref> In addition to their [[Grapefruit League]] games, the Phillies played two games against two of the [[2009 World Baseball Classic|World Baseball Classic]] teams. The Phillies defeated Team Canada (with Phillie [[Matt Stairs]]) on March 4, 9<U+2013>2,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aol.com.au/sport/story/Phillies-beat-Canada-in-WBC-warmup/1762471/index.html|title=Phillies beat Canada in WBC warmup|date=March 5, 2009|publisher=AOL Australia|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref> and lost to Team USA (with [[Jimmy Rollins]] and [[Shane Victorino]]) on March 5, 9<U+2013>6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/phillies/40834332.html|title=Kendrick shaky as Phils fall to Team USA|last=Martino|first=Andy|date=March 6, 2009|work=Philly.com|publisher=Philadelphia Inquirer|accessdate=March 12, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipukmKo5|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The team broke camp April 2 and headed north to play two "On Deck Series" games on April 3 and 4 against the Tampa Bay Rays at Citizens Bank Park; they split the series, winning 3<U+2013>2 and losing 9<U+2013>7.<ref name="schedule-April"/>

The Phillies finished the 2009 preseason with a record of 13<U+2013>19, 10 games behind the Grapefruit League-leading [[New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/standings/exhibition.jsp|title=Spring Training Standings|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 5, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/query?id=1249092307355061|archivedate=August 1, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Ryan Howard led all players in Spring Training with 10 [[home run]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/stats/sortable_player_stats.jsp?teamPosCode=All&statType=1&noHighlight=true&section1=1&timeFrame=1&statSet1=1&baseballScope=mlb&timeSubFrame=23&&sortByStat=HR|title=Major League Baseball Stats - Sortable Statistics (Sorted by home runs, 2009 Spring Training)|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 6, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuqifjT|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The team set spring training attendance-records for [[Bright House Field]] in 2009. They set a single-game record with 10,335 people in attendance on March 15 for a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/boxscore?gid=290315122 |title=St. Louis Cardinals/Philadelphia Phillies Box Score Sunday, March 15, 2009 |accessdate=March 23, 2009 |work= |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=March 15, 2009 }}</ref> The Phillies set the franchise's total spring training attendance record for Bright House Field, with 133,620 attending in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridagrapefruitleague.com/attendance.html|title=Florida's Grapefruit League: Attendance|publisher=Florida Grapefruit League Association|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref>

==Regular season==
===April===
[[File:Ryan Howard3.jpg|thumb|right|Ryan Howard ''(pictured)'' and Ra<U+00FA>l Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez hit grand slams in the same game against the Washington Nationals.|alt=A left-handed man in a red baseball jersey and white baseball pants with red pinstripes swings a black baseball bat at a baseball. His jersey reads "Howard" and "6" on the back in white print.]]
The Phillies began their 2009 season in front of a sold-out crowd of 44,532 at Citizens Bank Park on April 5, playing against the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref name="schedule-April">{{cite web|title = 2009 Phillies Schedule (April)|url = http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/schedule/index.jsp?c_id=phi&m=4&y=2009|accessdate = October 21, 2008|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipula2HV|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies, originally scheduled to play in the afternoon of April 6, earned the distinction of playing the opening game of the entire [[2009 Major League Baseball season]] after winning the 2008 World Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081110&content_id=3673753&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title=Phils to kick off '09 on national stage|date=November 10, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 11, 2008}}</ref> They lost the opener 4<U+2013>1 to the division-rival Braves, whose new [[Ace (baseball)|ace]], [[Derek Lowe]], pitched eight shutout innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_04_05_atlmlb_phimlb_1|title=Atlanta vs. Philadelphia - April 5, 2009|date=April 5, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 12, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipur6iwl|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies lost the next game,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_04_07_atlmlb_phimlb_1|title=Atlanta vs. Philadelphia - April 7, 2009|date=April 7, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 12, 2009}}</ref> and were in danger of losing the following night and dropping to 0<U+2013>3 before scoring eight runs in the bottom of the seventh inning for a 12<U+2013>11 come-from-behind win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_04_08_atlmlb_phimlb_1&mode=wrap|title=Atlanta vs. Philadelphia - April 8, 2009|date=April 8, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 12, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies lost their first game in Denver, but came from behind again in their next two games to take the second series from the [[Colorado Rockies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=PHI&t=b&year=2009|title=2009 Philadelphia Phillies Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=April 13, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies defeated the [[Washington Nationals]] in the opener of their third series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_04_13_phimlb_wasmlb_1&mode=gameday|title=Philadelphia vs. Washington - April 13, 2009|date=April 13, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 13, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipurx1bw|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> just hours after the passing of [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] broadcaster [[Harry Kalas]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2009/04/phillies_legend_kalas_dead_at.html?wprss=nationalsjournal|title=Phillies Legend Kalas Dead At 73|last=Harlan|first=Chico|date=April 13, 2009|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=April 13, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipurZYnq|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> but lost the third scheduled game of the series after the second was cancelled due to weather. In their series against the [[San Diego Padres]], the Phillies dropped the first two games as well; during the second game, closer [[Brad Lidge]] blew his first save in a Phillies uniform, breaking his streak of 47 consecutive saves extending back to the 2007 regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090418&content_id=4330922&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Lidge proven human as Phils fall|last=Jasner|first=Andy|date=April 19, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 19, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies won the Sunday afternoon matinee against the Padres, 5<U+2013>4, on a walk-off home run by Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez after trailing the entire game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_04_19_sdnmlb_phimlb_1&mode=gameday|title=San Diego vs. Philadelphia - April 19, 2009|date=April 19, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 19, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuslmKs|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> 

The Phillies' offense benefited from the postponement of the final game of the Padres' series, as they defeated the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] in the opener of their mid-week series, 11<U+2013>4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090421&content_id=4357514&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home&c_id=phi|title=Phillies support Moyer|date=April 21, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 23, 2009}}</ref> The next two games did not go as smoothly, as the Phillies were shut out through eight innings in the second game and nearly no-hit by Brewers starter [[Dave Bush]] in the third game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090422&content_id=4384226&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home&c_id=phi|title=Phillies' bats thwarted|date=April 22, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 23, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090423&content_id=4396010&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home|title=Hamels hurts more|date=April 23, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 23, 2009}}</ref> Phillies starter [[Cole Hamels]] was hit by a line drive in the fourth inning and exited the game; before departing, he had retired nine out of the ten batters he faced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090423&content_id=4394980&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Nearly blanked, Phillies lose game, ace|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=April 23, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 23, 2009}}</ref> Hitting the [[road (sports)|road]] for a series against the division-leading [[Florida Marlins]], the Phillies were shut out through eight innings in the first game of the series, only to score seven runs in the top of the ninth against [[power pitcher|power-throwing]] [[closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Matt Lindstrom]], winning the game, 7<U+2013>3, thanks to [[Shane Victorino]]'s first career regular season [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090424&content_id=4407904&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils sink Marlins with seven-run ninth|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=April 24, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 25, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iputAmJ0|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The following night's game offered another come-from-behind win for the Phillies, as they trailed in the ninth again to win in [[extra innings]], 6<U+2013>4,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090425&content_id=4425668&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils beat Marlins on Utley's single in 10th|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=April 25, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 26, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iputbp8c|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and the 13<U+2013>2 victory on April 26 capped the team's first series sweep.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090426&content_id=4434306&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away|title=Moyer masters Miami|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=April 26, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 27, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5iputz4hE|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Traveling to Washington for their second series against the Nationals, the Phillies fell behind in the seventh inning before a grand slam by Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez capped their 13<U+2013>11 victory; combined with [[Ryan Howard]]'s game-tying grand slam in the fifth inning, this was only the fourth time in Phillies history that teammates hit grand slams in the same game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090427&content_id=4450306&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies achieve rare offensive feat|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=April 27, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=April 28, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies split the remaining two games of the series with Washington, finishing with an April record of 11<U+2013>9, their second consecutive winning April.

===May===
[[File:Werth-crop.jpg|thumb|right|Jayson Werth tied a franchise record with four stolen bases, including home plate, on May 12.|alt=A right-handed man in a gray baseball uniform with red trim and a red batting helmet swings at a baseball with a baseball bat. His jersey reads "Werth" and "28" on the back in red letters.]]
The Phillies opened May against the [[Mets-Phillies rivalry|division-rival]] [[New York Mets]], losing the opening game of the month, 7<U+2013>4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090501&content_id=4511646&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home|title=Park struggles|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=May 1, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 2, 2009}}</ref> Back-to-back walks in the tenth inning of the Saturday afternoon game gave the Phillies their first win of the season over the Mets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_05_02_nynmlb_phimlb_1&mode=gameday|title=NY Mets vs. Philadelphia - May 2, 2009|date=May 2, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 2, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuubB5E|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> After a rainout, the Phillies opened their first series in St. Louis with the [[St. Louis Cardinals|Cardinals]]. They won the first game of the series on Howard's second grand slam in as many weeks after a [[List of baseball jargon (P)#pitchers' duel|pitchers' duel]] between starters [[Kyle Lohse]] and [[Joe Blanton]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090504&content_id=4558424&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Back home, Howard's slam sinks Cards|last=Rains|first=B.J.|date=May 4, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 5, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuv3S5q|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and completed the two-game series sweep with a 10<U+2013>7 victory on May 5, capped by a [[Jayson Werth]] three-run home run and a 4-for-5 performance from Victorino.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090505&content_id=4578530&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Victorino, Werth carry Phils over Cards|last=Rains|first=B.J.|date=May 5, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 6, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuvRj5O|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies' brief stop in New York was marred by a two-game series sweep; Phillies hitters were shut down by Mets starters [[Johan Santana]]<ref name="metsmay1">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090506&content_id=4588224&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Park sharp in loss|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=May 6, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 8, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuvqgyO|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and [[Mike Pelfrey]],<ref name="metsmay2">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090507&content_id=4609304&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Vet denied No. 250|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=May 7, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 8, 2009}}</ref> and [[closing pitcher|closer]] [[Francisco Rodriguez (baseball)|Francisco Rodriguez]] recorded saves in both games of the series.<ref name="metsmay1"/><ref name="metsmay2"/> The following series was barely better, as the Phillies dropped two games to the Braves.<ref name="Maysched">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/schedule/index.jsp?c_id=phi&m=5&y=2009|title=2009 Phillies Schedule (May)|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 16, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuwC2l3|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> 

On May 12, Werth stole four bases, including home plate, tying a Phillies record and leading to a 5<U+2013>3 win over the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]];<ref name="Werthsteals4">{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=290512122&prov=ap|title= Werth steals home, Phillies beat Dodgers 5-3|last=Gelston|first=Dan|work=Sports.Yahoo.com|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=May 16, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuwYdVK|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> however, the series result was the same as the previous one, as the Phillies dropped two games in the set to Los Angeles.<ref name="Maysched"/> 
Carrying a .500 winning percentage south from Philadelphia to Washington, the team visited the [[White House]] and was congratulated by President [[Barack Obama]] for their championship the previous season. The visit had been postponed from April 14 due to Kalas' death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090515&content_id=4749670&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies lauded for '08 title at White House: President Obama praises club for inspiring postseason run|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=May 15, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=July 27, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuzetKH|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> After meeting the President, the Phillies opened the series with a second consecutive extra-inning game, defeating the Nationals in 12 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=290515120|title=Philadelphia Phillies vs. Washington Nationals - Recap|date=May 15, 2009|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=May 17, 2009}}</ref> Because pitcher [[J. A. Happ]] had to enter Friday night's game in relief, the Phillies called up right-handed starting pitcher [[Andrew Carpenter (baseball)|Andrew Carpenter]] from [[Reading Phillies|Reading]] to start the second game of Saturday's [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] (a make-up of the postponement from April 15).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090515&content_id=4751852&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Never too late: Phils rally in 12th for win|last=Winston|first=Lisa|date=May 16, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 16, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuwymxZ|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Carpenter earned his first major league win in the rain-shortened second game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090517&content_id=4783348&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=In short stay, Carpenter earns first win|last=Winston|first=Lisa|date=May 16, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 17, 2009}}</ref> after Myers earned the win in the afternoon game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090516&content_id=4767162&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Myers comes through for Phillies|last=Winston|first=Lisa|date=May 16, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 17, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuy9fps|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Though Sunday's starter Park only pitched 1{{frac|1|3}} innings, the Phillies [[List of baseball jargon (S)#sweep|swept]] the series with the Nationals with an 8<U+2013>6 come-from-behind win, with new call-up [[Sergio Escalona]] earning his first major league win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2009_05_17_phimlb_wasmlb_1&mode=gameday|title=Philadelphia vs. Washington - May 17, 2009|date=May 17, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 17, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuxdk8B|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> This marked the first time since the [[2007 Philadelphia Phillies season|2007 season]] that rookies had won back-to-back starts for the Phillies (Hamels and [[Kyle Kendrick]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2007/VPHI02007.htm|title=The 2007 Philadelphia Phillies Regular Season Game Log|publisher=Retrosheet, Inc|accessdate=May 17, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuyVzwH|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies took two of three games in each of their next two series with the [[Cincinnati Reds]] and the [[New York Yankees]] to finish their road trip with an 8<U+2013>2 record. Though they lost two games against Florida, the final series of the month against Washington resulted in a second straight series sweep, as the Phillies defeated the Nationals in three consecutive games to finish the month with a 17<U+2013>11 record;<ref name="Maysched"/> the last game of the series was Moyer's 250th career victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090531&content_id=5066184&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home&c_id=phi|title=Lefty earns 250th win|last=Jasner|first=Andy|date=May 31, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuyumoa|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> With strong offensive performances in May, Howard and Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez became the first pair of Phillies to hit 10 home runs in the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090601&content_id=5088468&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Bastardo set to debut against Peavy|last=Burgin|first=Sandy|date=June 2, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 2, 2009}}</ref>

===June===
[[File:HappWarmup.jpg|thumb|right|upright|J. A. Happ pitched his first career complete-game shutout on June 27.|alt=A man in a blue baseball jersey, gray baseball pants, and a red baseball cap stands on a green field. He has a black baseball glove on his right hand.]]
The month of June saw the continuation of the Phillies' hot streak; from May 15 to June 4, the team compiled a 16<U+2013>4 record, culminating with a three-game sweep of the Padres on the Phillies' first trip to the West Coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/schedule/index.jsp?c_id=phi&m=6&y=2009|title=2009 Phillies Schedule (June)|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> In that series, rookie [[Antonio Bastardo]] made his major league debut, striking out five batters and allowing one earned run in six innings of work to earn his first career victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090602&content_id=5103796&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Ibanez homers twice|last=Burgin|first=Sandy|date=June 2, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> Traveling north to Los Angeles for a rematch of the [[2008 National League Division Series|previous year's playoff series]], the Phillies managed a split despite the bullpen's struggles. Lidge blew two saves in consecutive nights, taking the loss in the first game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090605&content_id=5170742&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Gem goes for naught|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=June 5, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> and allowing the game-tying home run in the other.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090606&content_id=5176542&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Lead slips from Lidge|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=June 6, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> The series was bookended by the team's first [[shutout]] of the season, a [[complete game]] by Hamels,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090604&content_id=5156644&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Hamels cruises in LA|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=June 4, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> and a second consecutive strong performance from Bastardo, who pitched five innings and allowed only two runs in a game that ended with a final score of 7<U+2013>2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090607&content_id=5198958&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Bastardo now 2-0|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=June 7, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> The final stop on the road trip was [[Citi Field]], where the Phillies faced off against the Mets. All three games were close, with two one-run wins in the series and two extra-inning victories for the Phillies, won by home runs from Utley and Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez on June 10 and 11.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYN/NYN200906100.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at New York Mets Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 10, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYN/NYN200906110.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at New York Mets Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 11, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> 

The team's strong stretch did not continue, however, as the Phillies entered the second period of interleague play with five consecutive series against the [[American League East]]. While they managed a single win against the [[Boston Red Sox]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200906140.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 14, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> it was followed by a six-game losing streak wherein the Phillies were swept by the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] and the [[Baltimore Orioles]];<ref name="2009splits"/> Philadelphia was outscored 38<U+2013>19 over the two series. The team showed promise in the first game of their [[2008 World Series|World Series rematch]] series with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]], winning 10<U+2013>1,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TBA/TBA200906230.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Tampa Bay Rays Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 23, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> but were defeated in the last two games of the series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TBA/TBA200906240.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Tampa Bay Rays Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 24, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TBA/TBA200906250.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Tampa Bay Rays Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 25, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> and lost a fourth straight game to Toronto on June 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TOR/TOR200906260.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Toronto Blue Jays Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 26, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> However, the Phillies were able to exact a modicum of revenge for both their [[1993 World Series]] defeat and the first series sweep by the Jays by winning the last two games. Happ played the role of [[List of baseball jargon (S)#stopper|stopper]] by pitching his first career complete game shutout,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TOR/TOR200906270.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Toronto Blue Jays Box Score and Play by Play|date=June 27, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> and Moyer followed by earning his 252nd victory in the following game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090628&content_id=5579346&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Lidge secures series win for Moyer, Phils|last=Singh|first=David|date=June 28, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> To close the month, the Phillies lost the opener of their next series with the Braves to finish the month with a 10<U+2013>16 record.<ref name="2009splits"/>

===July===
[[File:Shane Victorino World Series Parade.jpg|thumb|right|Shane Victorino was named to his first All-Star team as the winner of the Final Vote.|alt=A man in a red hooded sweatshirt and sunglasses raises his hand over his head, showing the "hang loose" sign (making a fist with the thumb and pinky raised).]]
Struggles continued for the Phillies to open July, as the Braves completed a three-game series sweep in the first two days of the month; however, a face-off with the Mets over the [[Independence Day]] weekend revitalized the team's fortunes. The Phillies swept their northern rivals as the Mets managed only three runs in three games. During the series, the team's [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2009 All-Stars]] were announced: Utley and Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez were elected as starters, and Howard was named as a reserve, one of four first basemen selected to the National League squad. It was also announced that Victorino was one of the five "Final Vote" candidates. Though the Phillies had played much better on the road to this point in the season, home-field advantage paid off the next night, as the offense chased Reds starter [[Johnny Cueto]] after {{frac|2|3}} of an inning by scoring nine runs; the team went on to score 10 in the first inning and 22 in the entire game.<ref name="22runs"/> Every Phillies starter had at least one hit, Werth hit an eighth-inning grand slam off of Reds infielder [[Paul Janish]], and Rollins and Victorino, at the top of the order, combined to go 7-for-9 with three doubles, a home run, nine runs scored, and five RBIs between them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200907060.shtml|title=Cincinnati Reds at Philadelphia Phillies Boxscore|date=July 6, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=July 10, 2009}}</ref> Though closer Lidge suffered a tough loss on July 7, sacrificing a run in the ninth inning to earn his fourth of the season, the Phillies bounced back with a dramatic ninth-inning win the following night. Victorino hit a walk-off single to drive in [[Pedro Feliz]] and solidify his victory in the All-Star Final Vote, which was announced the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090709&content_id=5787158&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Victorino victorious in Final Vote|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=July 9, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=July 10, 2009}}</ref> Werth was named to replace the New York Mets' [[Carlos Beltr<U+00E1>n]] on the All-Star roster due to injury; Victorino replaced Beltr<U+00E1>n as the starter in center field.

After the All-Star break<U+2014>during which the American League defeated the National League, 4<U+2013>3<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NLS/NLS200907140.shtml|title=All-Star Game Play by Play and Box Score|date=July 14, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref><U+2014>Moyer, [[Ryan Madson]], and [[J. C. Romero]] combined for a one-hit, complete-game shutout of the Marlins in the first game back,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/FLO/FLO200907160.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Florida Marlins Box Score and Play by Play|date=July 16, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> extending the Phillies' [[winning streak (sports)|winning streak]] to six games,<ref name="2009splits"/> and their record to 10<U+2013>3 in the month of July. The streak was extended to eight straight games as the Phillies swept Florida in three games of the series (one game was postponed due to weather).<ref name="July09">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/schedule/index.jsp?c_id=phi&m=7&y=2009|title=2009 Phillies Schedule (July)|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> Happ raised his record to 7<U+2013>0 on the season with another seven-inning shutout performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/FLO/FLO200907190.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Florida Marlins Box Score and Play by Play|date=July 19, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> The streak continued as the Phillies opened a series at home against the [[Chicago Cubs]]; [[Chad Durbin]] earned his first save in 11 months by pitching three scoreless innings of relief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090720&content_id=5953516&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils drub Cubs, notch ninth straight win|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=July 20, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> Werth's three-run home run in the 13th inning the next night gave the Phillies a walk-off win for their tenth consecutive,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200907210.shtml|title=Chicago Cubs at Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play by Play|date=July 21, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> but Chicago ended the season-high streak with a 10<U+2013>5 defeat on July 22.<ref name="July09"/> The Phillies won three of their next four, and bolstered their rotation by trading for [[Cliff Lee]]. The 2008 American League [[Cy Young Award]] winner came from the [[Cleveland Indians]] along with outfielder [[Ben Francisco]] on July 29; the Phillies gave up four minor leaguers<U+2014>catcher [[Lou Marson]], infielders [[Jason Donald]] and pitchers [[Carlos Carrasco]] and Jason Knapp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/dailypitch/2009-07-29-trade-deadline_N.htm|title=Phillies get 2008 Cy Young winner Cliff Lee from Tribe|last=Livingstone|first=Seth|date=July 29, 2009|work=USA Today|publisher=The Gannett Company|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> Lee and Francisco joined the Phillies in San Francisco after the Phillies' series victory over the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], and both started the final game in July. Lee pitched a complete-game four-hitter on July 31, allowing one run over nine innings of work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090731&content_id=6175446&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Lee superb in winning Phillies debut|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=July 31, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=August 1, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipv06jod|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies finished July with a 20<U+2013>7 record,<ref name="2009splits"/> their first 20-win month since May 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PHI/2001-schedule-scores.shtml|title=2001 Philadelphia Phillies Schedule, Box Scores and Splits|work=Sports Reference LLC|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 1, 2009}}</ref>

===August===
[[File:Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez Clearwater Threshers.jpg|thumb|right|Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez joined the rotation in August after Jamie Moyer was demoted to the bullpen.|alt=A right-handed man in a red baseball jersey and red baseball cap throws a baseball. His jersey and cap have a teal-colored shark on the front, and he is wearing a black baseball glove on his left hand.]]
The Phillies opened the month of August with three straight losses, but the stopper's role again fell to the rookie Happ, who pitched his second shutout of the season<U+2014>and the second of his career<U+2014>against the Rockies on August 5. He earned the team's 60th win of the season while allowing four hits and striking out ten batters for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200908050.shtml|title=Colorado Rockies at Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play-by-Play|date=August 5, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=August 6, 2009}}</ref> In accordance with his 8<U+2013>2 record and strong performances, Amaro announced that Happ would remain in the Phillies' starting rotation despite the team's acquisitions of Lee and [[Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/baseball/mlb/08/06/phillies.happ.ap/index.html#ixzz0NRddnfPs|title=Phillies GM: Happ won't go to bullpen to make room for Pedro|date=August 6, 2009|work=Sports Illustrated|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=August 6, 2009}}</ref> rumors regarding Happ's status had been rampant since Mart<U+00ED>nez' signing and during the trade season when Happ was rumored to be the centerpiece of a potential trade for the Blue Jays' [[Roy Halladay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/sports/20090801_Lee_deal_could_send_Happ_to_Phillies__bullpen.html|title=Lee deal could send Happ to Phillies' bullpen|last=Martino|first=Andy|date=August 1, 2009|work=Philadelphia Inquirer|accessdate=August 6, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ixk6TerW|archivedate=August 11, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.examiner.com/x-1164-Philadelphia-Phillies-Examiner~y2009m7d11-Happ-possibly-the-centerpiece-of-Halladay-deal|title=Happ possibly the centerpiece of Halladay deal|last=Gallen|first=Patrick|date=July 11, 2009|work=Philadelphia Phillies Examiner|accessdate=August 6, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ixk6toK4|archivedate=August 11, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gamecenter/recap/MLB_20090805_COL@PHI|title=Phils' Happ K's career-high 10, shuts out Rockies|date=August 5, 2009|agency=Associated Press|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=August 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delcotimes.com/articles/2009/08/05/sports/doc4a78ff38c1fdf185726488.txt|title=Colorado rocks Moyer, sending Phillies to loss|last=Lawrence|first=Ryan|date=August 5, 2009|work=Delaware County Times|accessdate=August 6, 2009}}</ref> New pitcher Lee stifled the Rockies the following day to win the series for the Phillies with a second consecutive strong performance, allowing one run over seven innings and allowing only six hits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090806&content_id=6275542&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Lee, Phils pleased with his home debut|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=August 6, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=August 6, 2009}}</ref> In the following series with Florida, however, the Phillies struggled. The Marlins swept all three games of the series,<ref name="2009splits"/> which included Victorino's first career ejection on several close calls by umpire [[Ed Rapuano]], and a crucial [[error (baseball)|error]] by Victorino's center field replacement, Werth, in the final game of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090809&content_id=6329920&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Ejectorino: Can't question ump from CF|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=August 9, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=August 10, 2009}}</ref> Moyer pitched against the Marlins in that game, a team against which he had prior success in his career<ref name="moyer1">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090809&content_id=6329620&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=After loss, Manuel upset with Phils' effort|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=August 10, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=August 10, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5j0vBvTpJ|archivedate=August 14, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> (13<U+2013>3, 2.87 ERA in 100{{frac|1|3}} innings pitched<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/split.cgi?n1=moyerja01&year=Career&t=p|title=Jamie Moyer Career Pitching Splits|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=August 10, 2009}}</ref>), and allowed two earned runs on eleven [[Single (baseball)|singles]] through five innings;<ref name="moyer1"/> however, with a rotation-high 5.47 ERA, the Phillies demoted Moyer to the bullpen to allow Mart<U+00ED>nez to start.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090810&content_id=6353302&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Pedro to make '09 debut Wednesday|last=Miller|first=Doug|date=August 11, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=August 10, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5j0vCLxOD|archivedate=August 14, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Francisco hit his second Phillies home run against the Cubs on August 11; it came in the 12th inning and scored the game-winning run for the Phillies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHN/CHN200908110.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Chicago Cubs Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 11, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> It became the first win of a three-game series sweep,<ref name="2009August"/> which Lee closed out with a third straight dominant performance (eight innings pitched, one run allowed, eight strikeouts).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHN/CHN200908130.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Chicago Cubs Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 13, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies took two of three games from the Braves in their next series,<ref name="2009August"/> and completed a three-game homestand against the Diamondbacks with a complete game from Lee, who carried a no-hitter into the sixth inning,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200908190.shtml|title=Arizona Diamondbacks at Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 19, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> and eight innings of three-run baseball from Blanton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200908200.shtml|title=Arizona Diamondbacks at Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 20, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> 

Mart<U+00ED>nez faced off against his former club on August 23, with the series tied 1<U+2013>1. Mets starter [[<U+00D3>liver P<U+00E9>rez]] allowed six runs in the first inning and was pulled in the middle of Mart<U+00ED>nez' first at-bat, down in the count 3<U+2013>0. [[<U+00C1>ngel Pag<U+00E1>n]] led off the Mets' first with an [[inside-the-park home run]] after the ball became lodged underneath the outfield wall. Mart<U+00ED>nez pitched six innings, allowing four runs, but the score was 9<U+2013>6 by the end of the eighth inning. Lidge allowed another run to score and had runners on first and second, thanks in part to a [[List of baseball jargon (B)#booted|booted]] base hit and an [[error (baseball)|error]] by [[Eric Bruntlett]]. The Mets had no outs and [[Jeff Francoeur]] was at the plate representing the [[List of baseball jargon (G)#Go-ahead run|go-ahead run]]. Francoeur hit a [[line drive]] over the second base bag, where Bruntlett caught it, stepped on second base, and tagged [[Daniel Murphy (baseball)|Daniel Murphy]] coming from first,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYN/NYN200908230.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at New York Mets Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 23, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> completing the 15th [[unassisted triple play]] in baseball's modern era and the second in [[History of the Philadelphia Phillies|Phillies history]] ([[Mickey Morandini]])<ref name="BruntlettTP">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=290823121|title=Pedro wins as unassisted triple play wraps up Phils' win vs. Mets|date=August 23, 2009|publisher=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=August 23, 2009}}</ref> in a game called "the league's quirkiest of the season".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091221&content_id=7837780&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Mets bear the Brunt of unassisted triple play|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|date=2009-12-30|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies closed the series with a 6<U+2013>2 win behind Lee's eighth straight victory (seven innings pitched, no earned runs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYN/NYN200908240.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at New York Mets Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 24, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> With a win on August 26, the Phillies claimed victory in the year's series over the Pirates;<ref name="2009splits"/> however, the Bucs won two games in a three-night set wherein the game-winning run was scored in the eighth inning or later each night. [[Andrew McCutchen]] hit a game-winning two-run home run off of Lidge in the ninth inning of the opener;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT200908250.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Pittsburgh Pirates Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 25, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> Howard hit a game-winning three-run shot for the Phillies in the top of the tenth on August 26 after the Pirates tied it in the ninth on a [[Brandon Moss]] home run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT200908260.shtml|title=Philadelphia Phillies at Pittsburgh Pirates Box Score and Play by Play|date=August 26, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> [[Garrett Jones]] set a Pirates rookie record with his 15th home run off of Happ in the eighth inning of the series finale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburgh.pirates.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090827&content_id=6653520&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=pit|title=Jones' two-run shot rescues Pirates|last=Mayo|first=Jonathan|date=August 27, 2009|work=Pirates.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies closed the month by taking two of three games from the Braves.<ref name="2009August">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/schedule/index.jsp?c_id=phi&m=8&y=2009|title=2009 Phillies Schedule (August)|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> For his 11 home run performance in August, Howard won the National League Player of the Month award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/2009-09-03-phillies-giants_N.htm|title=Pedro outduels Lincecum as Phillies edge Giants 2-1|date=September 4, 2009|agency=Associated Press|work=USA Today|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref>

===September===
[[File:UtleyFields.jpg|thumb|right|Chase Utley was one of four players on the 2009 Phillies squad to hit 30 home runs.|alt=A left-handed man in a gray baseball uniform with red trim and a red baseball cap stretches to reach a ball with his tan baseball glove; his foot is resting on a white square base.]]
The Phillies opened the month by taking two of a three-game series against the Giants, besting [[Jonathan S<U+00E1>nchez]], who threw a no-hitter earlier in the 2009 season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=290710126|title=Giants<U+2019> Jonathan Sanchez pitches no-hitter|last=McCauley|first=Janie|date=July 11, 2009|agency=|Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=September 9, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ji2Tg7OQ|archivedate=September 11, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and [[Tim Lincecum]], who won the 2008 NL Cy Young Award.<ref name="2009splits"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/story/11098799|title=Lincecum's Cy Young surprising until you check his numbers|last=Miller|first=Scott|date=November 11, 2008|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=September 9, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ji2U5yTp|archivedate=September 11, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> This was followed by a trip to Texas for a four-game series against the [[Houston Astros]]; the Phillies were unable to muster much offense during the series and were swept.<ref name="2009splits"/> On September 8, in the first game of the series against the [[Washington Nationals]], Iba<U+00F1>ez and Utley each hit their 30th home runs of the season, making them members of the 12th quartet of teammates in major league history to each reach 30 in a single season, joining Howard and Werth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090908&content_id=6860668&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies back Pedro with five solo shots|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=September 9, 2009=8|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 9, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ji2UqfRp|archivedate=September 11, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies offense backed Lee to his sixth win the following night, with Madson earning his second consecutive save after assuming the ''[[de facto]]'' closer's role from Lidge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090909&content_id=6879482&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Phillies lift Lee|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=September 9, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 12, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jq6ZvxqX|archivedate=September 16, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> However, the Phillies could not overcome a pair of three-run home runs by [[Adam Dunn]] and [[Ian Desmond]] to secure the sweep in the last game of the series, despite Stairs' grand slam; it was their third loss of the season to Washington in fifteen games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090910&content_id=6897244&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Rally falls short|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=September 10, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref> The Mets came to Philadelphia for their last series of the season, which began on September 11. The Phillies won game one, 4<U+2013>2, but the Mets came from behind in the second game of the series, scoring five runs in the final two innings to win 10<U+2013>9. Making up a postponed game from earlier in the season, the Phillies won the first game of a [[day-night doubleheader]] behind [[Kyle Kendrick]]'s first major league victory in 13 months. Eight shutout innings from Mart<U+00ED>nez in the [[List of baseball jargon (N)#nightcap|nightcap]] gave the Phillies a 1<U+2013>0 win, a 3<U+2013>1 win in the 4-game set,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090913&content_id=6944264&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Pedro's gem gives Phils twin-bill sweep|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=September 14, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 15, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jt8oLDb9|archivedate=September 18, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and a 12<U+2013>6 win in the season series.<ref name="2009splits">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PHI/2009-schedule-scores.shtml|title=2009 Philadelphia Phillies Schedule, Box Scores and Splits|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 6, 2008}}</ref> Mart<U+00ED>nez' eight innings also began a streak of 26 consecutive scoreless innings by Phillies pitchers: Madson followed with a scoreless ninth for his eighth save of the season;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200909132.shtml|title=New York Mets at Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play by Play|date=September 13, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> Cliff Lee pitched a complete game shutout against the Nationals the following night;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200909150.shtml|title=Washington Nationals and Philadelphia Phillies Box Score and Play by Play|date=September 15, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> and Blanton, Park, and Madson combined for eight scoreless innings against Washington on September 16 until [[Tyler Walker]] allowed a run in the top of the ninth inning, an RBI single by [[Willie Harris]] which scored [[Justin Maxwell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090916&content_id=6994112&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home&c_id=phi|title=Starter fans seven|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=September 16, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 17, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5k5eh6YHA|archivedate=September 26, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Hamels closed out the series with a strong performance, perfect through his first five innings and finishing with one run allowed in eight; with their 15th win over the Nationals, the Phillies matched their best season record against the franchise, set against the [[1976 Montreal Expos season|1976 Montr<U+00E9>al Expos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090917&content_id=7021752&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Hamels dominant as Phils sweep Nats|last=Jasner|first=Andy|date=September 17, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 18, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5k5eha7yH|archivedate=September 26, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> 

The Phillies continued to Atlanta, where they took two of three from the Braves, with Kendrick's second win and Lidge's 30th save in the first game of the series. Mart<U+00ED>nez was outdueled by [[Javier V<U+00E1>zquez]] in the second game of the series, but the Phillies avoided a loss by defeating the Braves, 4<U+2013>2, on September 20. A doubleheader followed against the Marlins; the Phillies won game one, while the Marlins won game two. In the [[rubber game]], Lidge blew his 11th save after a rain delay to give the Marlins a series victory, keeping the team's [[Magic number (sports)|number to clinch the division]] at five.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20090923&content_id=7116616&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Lidge can't save it|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=September 23, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 24, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5k5ehxQCo|archivedate=September 26, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Phillies and the Brewers split the next series at two games each, with Philadelphia winning the first and last game of the series. The Phillies returned to Citizens Bank Park for their final homestand to close out the season, opening with a fifth consecutive loss to the Astros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090928&content_id=7215212&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils fall as magic number remains three|last=Jasner|first=Andy|date=September 28, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 30, 2009}}</ref> However, the Phillies broke the streak with a 7<U+2013>4 win on September 29, thanks to a Feliz grand slam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090929&content_id=7227004&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils power way closer to NL East clinch|last=Jasner|first=Andy|date=September 29, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=September 30, 2009}}</ref> The following night, the Phillies clinched their third consecutive division title with a 10<U+2013>3 win over Houston, guaranteeing a split in the series and a playoff berth, and tying the franchise record for consecutive division titles set by [[Danny Ozark]]'s teams from 1976 to 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/columnists/bob_ford/20091001_Bob_Ford__Phillies_claim_NL_East_crown.html|title=Phillies claim NL East crown|date=October 1, 2009|work=Philadelphia Inquirer|accessdate=October 1, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kGGOonce|archivedate=October 3, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> After the clinching game, the Phillies rested most of their regular starters, six of whom had started over 150 games during the season; they lost four straight games while the regulars regained their strength, but won the final game of the season in extra innings as [[Paul Hoover]] hit a walk-off single in the bottom of the 10th inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/boxscore.jsp?gid=2009_10_04_flomlb_phimlb_1|title=Philadelphia 7, Florida 6|date=October 4, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 4, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies finished with a record of 93 wins and 69 losses, one game better than their record in the previous season.

