[[File:Cole Hamels 2008 v Reds.JPG|thumb|right|Cole Hamels left Citizens Bank Park during Game 2 of the Division Series to be with his wife, who was in labor.|alt=A left-handed man in a white baseball uniform and blue baseball cap with a red brim throws a baseball from a pitcher's mound.]]
{{main|2009 National League Division Series}}
The Phillies, as the #2 seed in the [[National League]], faced off against the [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] [[Colorado Rockies]] in the first round of the playoffs. [[Cliff Lee]] pitched a complete game in the opener of the series, shutting out the Rockies through {{frac|8|2|3}} innings before allowing a single run in the ninth. He threw 113 pitches in the game, in addition to getting a [[hit (baseball)|hit]] and a [[stolen base]] in his first postseason start.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20091007&content_id=7382162&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home&c_id=phi|title=Champs take Game 1|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 7, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 8, 2009}}</ref> The Rockies evened the series in the second game, as [[Cole Hamels]] left the stadium early to be with his wife, who went into labor with their first child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091009&content_id=7412160&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Hamels, wife welcome son into world|last=Bowman|first=Mark|date=October 9, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 10, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies staged comebacks twice to bring them within a run of tying the game, but could not close the door as [[Huston Street]] saved the game for [[Aaron Cook (baseball)|Aaron Cook]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910080.shtml|title=2009 National League Division Series (NLDS) Game 2|date=October 8, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 10, 2009}}</ref> 

After [[Charlie Manuel]] named [[Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez]] his Game 3 starter, the game was postponed a day due to the weather forecast of snow and record-low temperatures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091010&content_id=7420164&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Game 3 of Rox-Phils NLDS postponed|last=Schlegel|first=John|date=October 10, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 10, 2009}}</ref> The postponement prompted Manuel to change his plans, naming rookie left-hander [[J. A. Happ]] the new starter for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091010&content_id=7420776&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Given extra day, Phils to go with Happ|last=Bowman|first=Mark|date=October 10, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> Happ pitched three innings, allowing three runs, but Manuel brought [[Joe Blanton]] out of the bullpen, who pitched {{frac|2|2|3}} innings and allowed only one run. [[Brad Lidge]], after 11 [[blown save]]s during the regular season, preserved the win for the Phillies, a 6<U+2013>5 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/COL/COL200910110.shtml|title=2009 National League Division Series (NLDS) Game 3|date=October 11, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 12, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091011&content_id=7433082&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phils take Game 3, on verge of NLCS|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 11, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 12, 2009}}</ref> In a back-and-forth affair, the Phillies and Rockies traded leads through Game 4 at [[Coors Field]], but the Phillies scored three runs in the top of the ninth to win by one run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091012&content_id=7441094&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Amazing rally vaults Phillies into NLCS|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 12, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 13, 2009}}</ref> Combined with the sweeps in the other three Division Series, 2009 became the first year since the implementation of the wild card in 1995 that all four Championship Series berths were clinched on the road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091012&content_id=7441156&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Phils help set Division Series road mark|last=Miller|first=Doug|date=October 12, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 13, 2009}}</ref>

