===National League Championship Series===
[[File:Carlos Ruiz.jpg|thumb|right|Carlos Ruiz hit a three-run home run in Game 1 of the League Championship Series.|alt=A man in a blue baseball jersey, white baseball pants with red pinstripes, and a red baseball cap jogs across the baseball field wearing a tan catcher's mitt on his left hand.]]
{{main|2009 National League Championship Series}}
The [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] were the National League's #1 seed by virtue of the best record entering the playoffs; thus, the Phillies traveled to [[Chavez Ravine]] for the opener of the playoffs' second round, the [[List of most common Major League Baseball postseason matchups|fifth postseason meeting]] between the two clubs. [[James Loney]] opened the scoring for the Dodgers with a solo home run in the bottom of the second inning, but the Phillies answered back with a five-run fifth inning, chasing starter [[Clayton Kershaw]]. [[Manny Ram<U+00ED>rez]]' two-run home run in the bottom of the inning made the score 5<U+2013>4, but [[Ra<U+00FA>l Iba<U+00F1>ez]] followed with a three-run home run in the top of the eighth. Lidge, appearing in his third consecutive postseason game, notched his third consecutive save.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20091015&content_id=7463898&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away&c_id=phi|title=Opening statement|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 15, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091015&content_id=7461914&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Homers give Phils Game 1, home field|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 15, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref> Mart<U+00ED>nez started the second game for the Phillies, throwing 7 scoreless innings on 87 pitches. After his departure, the Phillies used five bullpen pitchers to get three outs in the eighth inning; those pitchers allowed three hits and two walks, allowing two runs to score. [[Jonathan Broxton]] saved the second game for the Dodgers, as Los Angeles won, 2<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAN/LAN200910160.shtml|title=2009 National League Championship Series (NLCS) Game 2|date=October 16, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 18, 2009}}</ref> 

The series moved to Philadelphia for the third game, and the Phillies capitalized on their home crowd immediately, scoring four runs in the first inning of the game. Lee continued his "superb" postseason performance<ref name="NLCSGame3Wrap"/> with an eight-inning shutout performance, allowing three singles and a stolen base. Lee and his [[Battery (baseball)|batterymate]] Ruiz had higher offensive production in Game 3 (three hits in six at-bats, three runs scored, one run batted in) than the entire Dodger lineup (three hits in twenty-seven at bats, no runs scored). The Phillies won the game, 11<U+2013>0.<ref name="NLCSGame3Wrap">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20091018&content_id=7489014&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home|title=Perfect-Lee done|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 18, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 19, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091018&content_id=7487434&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Philly bats soar; Cliff too tall for LA|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 18, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 19, 2009}}</ref> Howard continued to slug, hitting a two-run home run off of former Phillie [[Randy Wolf]] in the first inning of Game 4; with the [[run batted in]], he tied [[Lou Gehrig]]'s Major League record of eight consecutive postseason games with an RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091019&content_id=7494916&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Howard ties Gehrig's playoff RBI mark|last=Bowman|first=Mark|date=October 19, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}</ref> The Dodgers came back to score two runs on a defensive miscue in the fourth inning, adding one run in the fifth on a [[Matt Kemp]] home run and one in the sixth on a [[Casey Blake]] single. The Phillies got one back in the bottom of the sixth on a Victorino triple and a single by Utley, but were held scoreless until the bottom of the ninth. Los Angeles closer Broxton entered the game in the bottom of the eighth<U+2014>after [[George Sherrill]] allowed two runners to reach base<U+2014>and coaxed Werth to fly out. Broxton returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth, inducing a ground ball from Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez before walking [[Matt Stairs]] and hitting Ruiz. [[Greg Dobbs]] pinch-hit for the pitcher's spot, [[Line drive|lining out]] to [[third base]]. With two outs and two runners aboard, [[Jimmy Rollins]] hit a {{convert|99|mph|km/h|adj=on}} fastball to the right-center field gap, scoring [[Eric Bruntlett]] (who had pinch-run) and Ruiz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910190.shtml|title=2009 National League Championship Series (NLCS) Game 4|date=October 19, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/lee_jenkins/10/20/phillies.game.4/index.html?eref=sihp|title=Wily veteran Rollins puts Phillies on brink of return to World Series|last=Jenkins|first=Lee|date=October 19, 2009|work=Sports Illustrated|publisher=CNN / Sports Illustrated|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies hit four home runs in the fifth game, including two by [[Jayson Werth]], as Hamels allowed three runs in his second start of the series. The Phillies bullpen pitched {{frac|4|2|3}} innings in the game, allowing only one run as Philadelphia defeated Los Angeles, 10<U+2013>4. The win clinched the Phillies' first consecutive National League pennants in franchise history, and the first back-to-back World Series appearances by a National League franchise since the [[Atlanta Braves]] in 1995 and 1996. Howard was named the [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|MVP of the National League Championship Series]].<ref name="NLCSMVP">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4584440|title=Phillies' Howard takes home NLCS MVP|agency=Associated Press|date=October 22, 2009|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref>

