===World Series===
[[File:Jimmy Rollins.JPG|thumb|right|Jimmy Rollins predicted a Phillies<U+2013>Yankees World Series in May.|alt=A dark-skinned man in a red baseball jersey, white baseball pants with red pinstripes, and a red batting helmet walks on a baseball field while taking off his black and red batting gloves.]]
{{main|2009 World Series}}
The Phillies played the [[New York Yankees]] in a three-game series over the [[Memorial Day]] weekend during the regular season in May. Rollins, a harbinger of things to come, said:
<blockquote>How great would that be? A World Series here, us against the Yankees?<U+2026> We've proved we can put on a pretty good show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lisa-olson.fanhouse.com/2009/05/24/yankees-phillies-deliver-october-feel/ |title=Yankees, Phillies Deliver October Feel |last=Olson |first=Lisa|publisher=FanHouse.com |date=May 24, 2009|accessdate=October 25, 2009}}</ref></blockquote>
The Yankees defeated the Phillies, four games to two, to win the franchise's record 27th World Series championship. The Yankees had home field advantage for the series, due to an [[American League]] victory in the [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2009 All-Star Game]]. In addition to the 27th championship for New York, several records were tied, extended, or broken during the Series, including postseason wins ([[Andy Pettitte]] with 18), home runs in a World Series (Utley with 5), strikeouts by a batter in a World Series (Howard with 13), saves in a World Series ([[Mariano Rivera]] with 11), and RBI in a single World Series game ([[Hideki Matsui]] with 6).

====Game 1====
{{Linescore||Road='''Philadelphia'''|RoadAbr=PHI|R1=0|R2=0|R3=1|R4=0|R5=0|R6=1|R7=0|R8=2|R9=2|RR=6|RH=9|RE=1|
Home=New York|HomeAbr=NYY|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=1|HR=1|HH=6|HE=0|
RSP=[[Cliff Lee]] (2<U+2013>0)|HSP=[[CC Sabathia]] (3<U+2013>0)|WP=Lee (3<U+2013>0)|LP=Sabathia (3<U+2013>1)|SV=|RoadHR=[[Chase Utley]] 2<U+00D7> (2)|HomeHR=}}
The two previous years' American League [[Cy Young Award]] winners started the game: [[CC Sabathia]], for the Yankees; and Lee, for the Phillies. Sabathia, who had been 3<U+2013>0 in the postseason to date, pitched seven innings and allowed two [[earned run]]s on four hits; Lee, however, pitched a [[complete game]] and allowed no earned runs to go the distance for the second time during the 2009 postseason. The Phillies offense was paced by Utley, who walked in the first inning to set a record of 26 consecutive postseason games reaching base, and hit solo home runs in the third and sixth innings. Philadelphia led 2<U+2013>0 until the eighth inning, when an Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez single scored Rollins and Victorino, and added two more runs in the top of the ninth inning on a Victorino single and a Howard double. The Phillies allowed an unearned run in the bottom of the ninth when Rollins committed a throwing error, tossing the ball past Howard at first base and into the Yankee dugout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910280.shtml|title=2009 World Series Game 1|first=2009-10-28|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 29, 2009}}</ref>

====Game 2====
{{Linescore|
|Road=Philadelphia|RoadAbr=PHI
|R1=0|R2=1|R3=0|R4=0|R5=0|R6=0|R7=0|R8=0|R9=0|RR=1|RH=6|RE=0
|Home='''New York'''|HomeAbr=NYY
|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=1|H7=1|H8=0|H9=x|HR=3|HH=8|HE=0
|RSP=[[Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez]] (0<U+2013>0)|HSP=[[A. J. Burnett]] (0<U+2013>0)|WP=Burnett (1<U+2013>0)|LP=Mart<U+00ED>nez (0<U+2013>1)|SV= [[Mariano Rivera]] (4)
|RoadHR=|HomeHR= [[Mark Teixeira]] (1), [[Hideki Matsui]] (1)
|}}

The Phillies scored first for the second game in a row in the second inning; [[Ra<U+00FA>l Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez]] hit a [[ground rule double]], and a [[Matt Stairs]] single off of [[A. J. Burnett]] drove him in. It was the only run allowed by the New York pitching staff.<ref name="game2bref">{{cite web| url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910290.shtml|title=2009 World Series Game 2|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref> [[Mark Teixeira]] tied the game with a solo home run in the fourth inning, and [[Hideki Matsui]] broke the tie in the sixth with another, giving the Yankees their first lead. [[Chan Ho Park]] allowed an RBI single to [[Jorge Posada]] after Mart<U+00ED>nez put two baserunners on in the top of the seventh.<ref>{{cite news |first=Bryan|last=Hoch|title=Yanks take Classic duel to pull even|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7572446&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|publisher=MLB.com|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref> Burnett departed after seven innings, replaced by [[Mariano Rivera]] in the eighth. The Phillies put two runners on with a walk to [[Jimmy Rollins]] and a single by [[Shane Victorino]] with one out in the eighth. However, [[Chase Utley]] grounded into an inning-ending double play ending on a close play at first base that drew controversy.<ref>{{cite news |first=David|last=Waldstein|title=In World Series, Umpires Find Themselves Back in Center of Dispute|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/30/sports/baseball/30umps.html?_r=1|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=October 30, 2009}}</ref> Rivera completed the ninth inning for his 38th postseason [[Save (baseball)|save]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Erik|last=Boland|title=Rivera gets six-out save as Yankees win Game 2, 3-1|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/rivera-gets-six-out-save-as-yankees-win-game-2-3-1-1.1557551|publisher=[[Newsday]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref>

====Game 3====
