|RoadHR=[[Alex Rodriguez]] (1), [[Nick Swisher]] (1), Matsui (2) |HomeHR=[[Jayson Werth]] 2<U+00D7> (2), [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] (1)
|}}

After an 80-minute rain delay, the Phillies scored first in the second inning with [[Jayson Werth]]'s lead-off home run followed by a bases-loaded walk and a [[sacrifice fly]].<ref name="game3bref">{{cite web| url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910310.shtml|title=2009 World Series Game 3|date=October 31, 2009|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> In the fourth inning, [[Alex Rodriguez]] hit a ball down the right field line, which struck a camera at the fence and was ruled a home run after review.<ref name="cameramove">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594160&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Camera moved after A-Rod homer|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009}}</ref> [[Nick Swisher]] opened the top of the fifth inning with a double and scored on a single to center field by [[Andy Pettitte]]. Jeter followed with a single, and both he and Pettite were driven in by a [[Johnny Damon]] double. [[J. A. Happ]] replaced Hamels and  allowed a solo home run to Swisher in the sixth inning. Werth answered with a second home run of the game leading off the bottom of the sixth.<ref name="game3bref"/> [[Mariano Rivera]] recorded his 38th career postseason save to close out the Yankees' second consecutive win.

====Game 4====
{{Linescore|
|Road='''New York'''|RoadAbr=NYY
|R1=2|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=2|R6=0|R7=0|R8=0|R9=3|RR=7|RH=9|RE=1
|Home=Philadelphia|HomeAbr=PHI
|H1=1|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=0|H7=1|H8=1|H9=0|HR=4|HH=8|HE=1
|RSP=Sabathia (3<U+2013>1)|HSP=[[Joe Blanton]] (0<U+2013>0)|WP=[[Joba Chamberlain]] (1<U+2013>0)|LP=[[Brad Lidge]] (1<U+2013>1)|SV=Rivera (5)
|RoadHR=|HomeHR=Utley (3), [[Pedro Feliz]] (1)
|}}

The Yankees opened the scoring in the first inning with two runs, but the Phillies answered with back-to-back doubles by [[Shane Victorino]] and [[Chase Utley]] in the bottom of the inning. The Phillies tied the game in the bottom of the fourth as [[Ryan Howard]] singled, [[Stolen base|stole]] second, and scored on a single by [[Pedro Feliz]]. Replays showed that Howard did not touch [[home plate]] as he slid across; however, the Yankees did not appeal. Swisher led off the fifth inning with a walk, scoring on a single by Derek Jeter, and [[Melky Cabrera]] scored on a single by Damon. Park relieved Blanton in the seventh and held the Yankees scoreless. Chase Utley hit his third [[home run]] of the series in the bottom of the seventh with two outs. [[D<U+00E1>maso Mart<U+00E9>]] struck out Howard to end the inning. After a game-tying home run by Feliz, Lidge entered the game in the ninth and gave up a two-out single to Damon.<ref name="WSG4">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200911010.shtml|title=2009 World Series Game 4|date=November 1, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=November 3, 2009}}</ref> With Teixeira batting, Damon stole second and advanced to third as the base was uncovered due to the [[Baseball positioning|pull shift]] against Teixeira.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594166&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Johnny lately: Yanks' 9th makes it a 3-1 Series |accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Brian|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009}}</ref> Rodriguez put the Yankees ahead with a double to left field, scoring Damon. Posada added to that lead with a single which scored Teixeira, who had singled, and Rodriguez. [[Mariano Rivera]] entered in the bottom of the ninth and notched his second save of the series.<ref name="WSG4"/>

====Game 5====
[[File:Ryan Madson.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Ryan Madson earned his first career World Series save in Game 5.|alt=A man in a blue baseball jersey and wearing a catcher's mitt on his left hand squats in a bullpen. He has a catcher's mask made of leather and metal atop his head.]]
{{Linescore|
|Road=New York|RoadAbr=NYY
|R1=1|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=1|R6=0|R7=0|R8=3|R9=1|RR=6|RH=10|RE=0
|Home='''Philadelphia'''|HomeAbr=PHI
|H1=3|H2=0|H3=3|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=2|H8=0|H9=x|HR=8|HH=9|HE=0
|HSP=Lee (3<U+2013>0)|RSP=Burnett (1<U+2013>0)|WP=Lee (4<U+2013>0)|LP=Burnett (1<U+2013>1)|SV=[[Ryan Madson]] (1)
|RoadHR=|HomeHR=Utley 2<U+00D7> (5), [[Ra<U+00FA>l Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez]] (1)
|}}
The Yankees scored first for the second straight game, but Utley gave the lead back to Philadelphia on a three-run home run. Werth and Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez drove in Utley and Howard in the third inning, which chased the starter, Burnett. [[David Robertson (baseball)|David Robertson]] allowed another run to score on a [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] groundout. [[Eric Hinske]], who entered as a [[pinch hit|pinch-hitter]], scored on a ground out by Johnny Damon. Utley tied [[Reggie Jackson]]'s record for most home runs in a World Series with a solo home run in the seventh inning, his fifth of the series. Howard struck out for the 12th time in the series, tying [[Willie Wilson (baseball)|Willie Wilson's]] 1980 record for most strikeouts in a World Series. Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez hit a solo home run to chase pitcher [[Phil Coke]]. After being hit in the hand in the first inning, Victorino was [[Defensive substitution|replaced defensively]] in the eighth inning by [[Ben Francisco]]. Lee left the game after allowing two runs to score, and Park gave up a sacrifice fly to [[Robinson Can<U+00F3>]] to add another earned run to Lee's line. [[Ryan Madson]] entered in the ninth to close the game, allowing one run on a double play but earning his first career World Series save.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200911020.shtml|title=2009 World Series Game 5|date=November 2, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref>

====Game 6====
{{Linescore|
|Road=Philadelphia|RoadAbr=PHI
|R1=0|R2=0|R3=1|R4=0|R5=0|R6=2|R7=0|R8=0|R9=0|RR=3|RH=6|RE=0
|Home='''New York'''|HomeAbr=NYY
|H1=0|H2=2|H3=2|H4=0|H5=3|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=x|HR=7|HH=8|HE=0
|HSP=Petitte (1<U+2013>0)|RSP=Mart<U+00ED>nez (0<U+2013>1) |WP=Petitte (2<U+2013>0)|LP=Mart<U+00ED>nez (0<U+2013>2) |SV=
|RoadHR=[[Ryan Howard]] (1)|HomeHR=Matsui (3)
|}}
The Yankees scored first when Matsui hit a two-run home run with Rodriguez on base after a walk. The Phillies responded with a triple by Ruiz, who scored on a sacrifice fly by Rollins in the top of the third inning. Matsui added to the Yankee lead with a bases-loaded single in the bottom of the inning, scoring Jeter and Damon. Mart<U+00ED>nez was relieved after four innings by Durbin, who allowed a [[ground rule double]] to Jeter, who later scored on a Teixeira single. Durbin hit Rodriguez and was relieved by Happ after recording one out. Happ allowed a two-run double to Matsui, his fifth and sixth RBI of the game which tied a World Series record for most RBI in a single game set by [[Bobby Richardson]] in the [[1960 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620234&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Matsui ties World Series record with 6 RBIs |accessdate=November 4, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=November 4, 2009}}</ref> 

In the sixth inning, Howard's home run following a walk issued to Utley brought the game to 7<U+2013>3. After Ib<U+00E1><U+00F1>ez hit a double into right field, [[Joba Chamberlain]] relieved Pettitte, allowing no further runs in the inning. In the top of the eighth inning, [[Damaso Mart<U+00E9>]] struck out Howard, which set a new World Series record for most strikeouts by a batter in a single series (13).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616316&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Howard sets Series record for strikeouts |accessdate=November 5, 2009|last=Bowman|first=Mark|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=November 5, 2009}}</ref> After the strikeout, Mart<U+00E9> was relieved by Rivera in a non-save situation, who allowed one hit and one walk before closing out the game and the Yankees' 27th championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200911040.shtml|title=2009 World Series Game 6|date=November 4, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref>

==Awards==
{{seealso|List of Major League Baseball awards}}
The 2009 Phillies captured the [[Warren C. Giles Trophy]], as winners of the National League pennant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091021&content_id=7515920&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Werthy of repeat: Philly swaggers into WS|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=October 22, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=October 29, 2009}}</ref> Individual players to win awards for their regular and postseason performances included Rollins, who won a third straight [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award]] at shortstop; Victorino, who won a second Gold Glove in the outfield;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091111&content_id=7652510&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Rollins, Victorino retain Gold Glove crowns|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=November 11, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref> Utley, who won his fourth consecutive [[Silver Slugger Award]] at second base;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/sports/times/index.ssf?/base/sports-0/1258094743148620.xml&coll=5|title=Utley wins another Silver Slugger|date=November 13, 2009|work=Trenton Times|publisher=NJ.com|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref> and Howard, who was named the [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player|Most Valuable Player of the National League Championship Series]].<ref name="NLCSMVP"/>

