*{{note label|Stats|A|A}}Statistical leaders must qualify by Major League Baseball's criteria to be considered "leaders".

;Game log
*{{note label|Werth|a|a}}[[Jayson Werth]] tied a franchise record by stealing four bases, including [[home plate]], in the Phillies' 5<U+2013>3 victory over the Dodgers.<ref name="Werthsteals4"/>
*{{note label|July6|b|b}}The Phillies tied a franchise record by scoring ten runs in the first inning, and set season highs in hits (21) and runs scored (22). The 22 runs was the fifth-most in [[History of the Philadelphia Phillies|franchise history]] and was the biggest defeat in the history of the opposing [[Cincinnati Reds]] franchise.<ref name="22runs">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090706&content_id=5730404&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Behind Victorino, Phils score 22 in rout|last=Gurian-Peck|first=David|date=July 7, 2009|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=July 10, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ipuzNugn|archivedate=August 6, 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref>
*{{note label|August23|c|c}}[[Eric Bruntlett]] turned the 15th [[unassisted triple play]] in the modern era of [[Major League Baseball]] history. It was the second in Phillies history ([[Mickey Morandini]]) and the second game-ending unassisted triple play ([[Johnny Neun]], 1927).<ref name="BruntlettTP"/>
